1411","1390–1429":"1390–1429","1404":"1404","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","Abt 1390":"about 1390","1429":"1429","1390":"1390","Sydenham Damerel, Devon, England":"Sydenham Damerel, Devon, England","Cornwall, Somerset, England (United Kingdom)":"Somerset, England","Stottiscombe, Sutcombe, Devonshire, England":"Sutcombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Stottiscombe, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, Somerset , England (United Kingdom)":"Cornwall, England","Mount Wise, Devon, England":"Mount Wise, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Callahan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Brennan, Bridie, Clancy, Connor, Conor, Delma, Eamon, Gearold, Keane, Kieran.","Irish (Munster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceallachán</i>’, a diminutive of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i>, probably meaning ‘bright-headed’, from <i>cen</i> ‘head’ + <i>lach</i> ‘light’. This name was borne by a 10th-century king of Munster, from whom many present-day bearers of the surname claim descent."],"variants":[{"name":"Calligan","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Callahan  ."]},{"name":"Calliham","meanings":["Altered form of Irish   Callahan  , influenced by the common element found in English habitational names, <i>-ham</i>. Compare   Callaham  ."]},{"name":"Callihan","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Callahan  ."]},{"name":"Calahan","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Callahan  . This surname is now rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Callaham","meanings":["Irish: most probably an altered form of Irish   Callahan  , influenced by the common element of English habitational names, <i>ham</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Colahan","meanings":["variant of   Callahan  .","variant of <b>Colohan</b>, from <b>Mac Uallocháin</b> ‘son of <i>Uallachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>uallach</i> ‘proud’.","Irish:"]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Callahan was born in 1355, in Devon, England. She married Robert Britt in 1374, in Sutcombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1429, in Sydenham Damerel, Devon, England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1355–1429":"1355–1429","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1375–1411":"1375–1411","1390–1429":"1390–1429","1404":"1404","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","Abt 1390":"umbes 1390","1429":"1429","1390":"1390","Sydenham Damerel, Devon, England":"Sydenham Damerel, Devon, England","Cornwall, Somerset, England (United Kingdom)":"Somerset, England","Stottiscombe, Sutcombe, Devonshire, England":"Sutcombe, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stottiscombe, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, Somerset , England (United Kingdom)":"Cornwall, England","Mount Wise, Devon, England":"Mou